My team’s trying out using ML for ball recognition this year, and I’ve been messing around with WPILib’s Axon, but when it finishes training it never plots anything on the chart. I’ve been following the steps in this document. Any idea what I could doing wrong?

What settings are you using for your training? Also, what how many images are in your dataset? I know for me when I did not have enough images in my dataset initially it would not train at all. Axon has been very finicky for me, sometimes on certain settings it would do the same. I would suggest taking a look at this thread: Any success with Axon?, it helped me quite a bit.

What are you using for a dataset? If you are using the field images, I think there is a missing step. You need to convert the video to images before exporting.

Also, following the ideas in this thread helped me a lot.

Any success with Axon? Programming
Has anyone had any luck with the new Axon tool from WPILib? I was able to get the tool up and running, but I haven’t had any success creating trained models that can identify anything. I created some data sets from Open Images but my model was not able to identify the objects reliably in a test video. I also tried creating a couple data sets with Supervisely, but I was not able to train models with them, they never generate any checkpoints in Axon.

It is confusing the way it’s described in the Axon UI, but I think you want to set your Percent Evaluation to something closer to 30. (The tool tip suggests that this is the number of images used for training, but I believe it is actually the number of images set aside for evaluation.) At 75%, you only have about 40 images in your training set.

You probably need more images in your data set.

I also had Axon sometimes fail to finish training randomly, and then it would work fine when I try again with the same data set as input. It got more stable when I closed a few applications (particularly Google Chrome and the preview window) to free up more system memory.

I think the smallest dataset I successfully trained had about 700 or so.

I don’t know if I can share the images directly, but I had pretty good initial results with cargo detection by training off of a generic set of about 1,600 images from the Open Images project. You can import these into Axon using the Create Dataset button, then search for “ball” when you get to OpenImages.

Start there and see if you can get that to train. It took awhile (maybe 2 hours) but it generated several usable checkpoints.
